This is an Introductory Reading and Writing course for fluent speakers of Chinese. The objective of the course is to lay a solid foundation in both Pinyin Romanization and Chinese characters, learning to produce and recognize approximately 600-650 characters. Students focus mostly on reading and writing skills, and the class provides preparation for Intermediate Modern Chinese.&#8232;&#8232;

Students appreciated the “well-roundedness of [their] Chinese education.” The class “involved more than just learning Chinese, but also included various aspects of the Chinese culture.” &#8232;&#8232;

Students stated that Professor Wu was “excellent” and that she “definitely made efforts to make sure that students understood the material.” Professor Wu gave them “mini history lessons about China” which students found useful.&#8232;&#8232;

Although this is an introductory course for fluent speakers, students found that without previous exposure to written Chinese, the course was rather difficult. A student commented that “if [one] did not go to a Chinese school or was never taught basic Chinese when [one] was younger, the course would be too fast-paced.” Students recommended that students coming in with no written Chinese background “look over course lessons before the course begins.”

